 # Decisions Today
 
+- Start the refine verification pass as soon as a live review report exists, and keep the old report-driven effect only as a backstop so duplicate starts stay blocked by report id.
+- Solve auto-detect wine ambiguity in the form with an optional reveal path instead of forcing a beverage-type switch: reviewers can keep `Auto-detect` selected and still enter appellation, vintage, or varietals when the COLA application includes them.
+- Make batch reviewer-facing status copy truthful by collapsing engine `fail` into `Needs review` on stream, dashboard, and batch-summary surfaces while leaving the underlying wire status untouched.
+- Use a simple deterministic batch ETA (`5 seconds per remaining label`) rather than the prior moving-average estimate, which bounced around and overstated precision.
+- For the `TTB-210` quick-scan follow-up, bias readable-but-nonspecific OCR text back to `uncertain`; reserve `unlikely-label` for uploads that are still short on readable text and lack even weak label cues.
+- For the same follow-up, remove the intake quick-scan warning entirely; let Verify run immediately and keep any readability / non-label call on the post-Verify result path.
+- Record the hidden-intake quick-scan behavior explicitly in `docs/specs/TTB-210/user-flow-map.md`, `docs/specs/TTB-210/observability-plan.md`, and `evals/results/2026-04-19-ttb-210-relevance-recovery.md`.
 - For `TTB-210`, add a cheap OCR-backed `POST /api/review/relevance` preflight ahead of extract-only instead of spending another model/provider call just to classify upload relevance.
 - For `TTB-210`, treat the relevance result as orchestration advice only: `likely-label` starts prefetch, `uncertain` stays neutral, and `unlikely-label` warns at intake but still allows explicit continue-anyway into the canonical review path.
 - For `TTB-210`, keep the relevance contract bounded and privacy-safe: decision, confidence, beverage hint, and coarse signals only, with no raw OCR text exposed to the client.
