+## Quick Setup
+
+- Start app with the normal developer run command (`npm run dev` or your normal launch flow).
+- Open a standard desktop viewport (ideally 1440px wide).
+- Keep the browser zoom at 100%.
+- Make sure the app can call the API locally (Toolbench COLA sample flows require the API routes).
+
+---
+
+## 00:00–00:15 — First impression and login
+
+### What you do
+1. Open the app URL.
+2. Wait for the boot screen.
+3. Click through the prototype sign-in.
+
+### What to say
+"Hi, and welcome. We’ll walk through the full assistant experience from login to batch export.
+
+You’ll notice a short startup pause first. That delay is intentional: it gives icon fonts and surface styles time to settle so the interface renders fully before you start.
+
+From here, this is just a local prototype login. Pick either path to get into the system, and you’ll land in the intake page."
+
+### What you should see
+- A boot panel with: 
+  - `Preparing label verification experience`
+  - A short progress bar.
+- Authentication screen with options:
+  - `Sign in with your work ID card (PIV/CAC)`
+  - `Sign in with your Treasury username (SSO)`
+- In SSO mode, a small user id field and `Continue` button.
+
+### Notes for recording
+- **Pause 5+ seconds here** at startup and auth so the icon set looks stable before narration continues.
+
+---
+
+## 00:15–00:45 — App layout, identity, and where testing tools live
+
+### What you do
+1. Sign in (you can use `SSO` flow and enter any value, it is accepted in prototype mode).
+2. On the signed-in header, note:
+   - Left side: mode tabs (`Single` / `Batch`).
+   - Right side: Help launcher and identity menu.
+3. Confirm the floating **Toolbench** panel is visible on the right edge.
+
+### What to say
+"You’re in the assessor workspace now. I use this for two things: a normal single review flow, and a batch review flow when teams need throughput.
+
+In the lower-right there’s the Toolbench. It is a demo assistant panel for quickly loading real COLA records, synthetic cases, and batch fixtures.
+
+This lets you verify behavior rapidly without hunting through manual file setup."
+
+### What you should see
+- Header title: **TTB Label Verification Assistant**
+- Bottom-right panel called **Toolbench** with tabs:
+  - Samples
+  - Upload
+  - Actions
+
+---
+
+## 00:45–02:00 — Single-label path with real data (stormwood preset)
+
+### What you do
+1. Keep **Single** tab active.
+2. In Toolbench → **Samples** tab, open the sample list if needed.
+3. Load a second preset: **`stormwood-wines-semillon-wine`** (or a similarly named *Stormwood Semillon* row).
+4. Wait for intake to fill image + form fields.
+5. Click **Verify Label**.
+
+### What to say
+"I’m deliberately using a different preset from the happy-path spirit case so we can show how the app handles wine-class equivalence.
+
+The form is pre-filled from a real COLA Cloud record, including the image, so we can focus on review quality rather than data entry.
+
+Now we run verification."
+
+### What you should see
+- Intake form now has populated fields including:
+  - `Brand name`, `Fanciful name`, `Class/type`, `Alcohol content`, `Net contents`, and wine-specific fields such as `Appellation`, `Vintage`, origin values.
+- A clear **Verify** action.
+- Processing screen with step list / timer while inference runs.
+
+### What to watch
+- The system enforces a **~3.5s warm-up** before entering the app; keep this in the take.
+- If you want a more pronounced demonstration of confidence behavior, use the preset’s real-world edge-case context (`table white wine` vs `SEMILLON`), and explain that this is handled through normalization + taxonomy logic.
+
+---
+
+## 02:00–02:50 — Result screen deep dive (what the reviewer sees)
+
+### What you do
+1. On results, let the verdict banner read.
+2. Read the subtitle and action row.
+3. Open one non-warning field row with **Show evidence**.
+4. Open the **Government warning** row.
+5. Scroll and observe the field order and status semantics.
+6. Use **Escape** to close any expanded row.
+
+### What to say
+"This is the core reviewer surface.
+
+The banner tells you whether the label is auto-recommended or needs a closer look. It is intentionally high-level, because the real work is in the field rows.
+
+Each row has three parts to read:
+- what the application said,
+- what the extractor read from the label,
+- status (`pass`, `review`, `fail`, `info`).
+
+I’m going to expand evidence next so you can see the proof trail and confidence signals for each field.
+
+For warning checks, I expect you to get richer evidence with the extracted full text and match details — that’s where these checks usually need human judgment.
+
+When review is uncertain or confidence is low, that row is highlighted as `review` and the system nudges you to verify manually.
+
+Notice the row-level affordance uses explicit text: **Show evidence / Hide evidence** and a chevron so it is obvious it is interactive."
+
+### What you should see
+- Verdict banner and confidence/caution language.
+- Row ordering by status then severity.
+- Expanded row panel appears below the row.
+- For warning row, there is a warning-specific evidence view.
+- Keyboard support:
+  - `ArrowDown` / `ArrowUp` to move among rows,
+  - `Escape` to collapse,
+  - `N` to start a new review.
+- `Show evidence` labels next to each row.
+
+### Narration pace guidance
+- Let this section breathe: **60–90 seconds** total.
+
+---
+
+## 02:50–03:35 — Back to active workflow and review controls
+
+### What you do
+1. Click **Start a new check** / breadcrumb.
+2. Re-open Toolbench quickly and return to **Samples**.
+3. Optionally switch to another preset if you want to show another behavior:
+   - `harpoon` (rotated text/wrapper case)
+   - `warning occluded` (reject/review behavior)
+
+### What to say
+"You get right back into intake, with the same app shell and same review controls.
+
+This is deliberate: the tool should feel predictable whether you’re doing one label or many.
+
+The reviewer remains in control when a row is marked for review; the app does not hide uncertainty.
+
+The system intentionally favors conservative outcomes — if there is any low-confidence area, it surfaces it as review instead of over-confidently approving.
+"
+
+---
+
+## 03:35–05:00 — Full batch flow (required for this showcase)
+
+### What you do
+1. Click the **Batch** tab.
+2. In Toolbench (or on the batch screen), click **Load COLA sample pack**.
+3. Wait for:
+   - 10 sample images
+   - CSV loaded.
+   - Matching review panel.
+4. Review matching status counts:
+   - `matched`, `ambiguous`, `unmatched`.
+5. Resolve anything unresolved if present:
+   - choose matching candidates,
+   - drop unmatched items,
+   - use row/image pairing controls.
+6. Click **Start Batch** only when `Start` is enabled.
+7. Watch the stream progress to completion.
+8. Enter the **Batch Results** screen.
+
+### What to say
+"Now we’re in throughput mode.
+
+The goal here is to show the review posture for every label and not lose track of what you already decided.
+
+Toolbench here loads a real, structured batch with a matching CSV so we can jump straight to preflight and processing.
+
+The preflight step is important: it shows matched pairs and flags ambiguous/unmatched rows before compute starts. It prevents hidden surprises later.
+
+The first thing I check is the matching panel because once you’ve started, any ambiguous pairing is your review responsibility.
+
+Then I start the batch and let it stream. This is where people feel the app is slow in bad prototypes — so we keep per-stage feedback visible while results roll in.
+"
+
+### What to see in Matching Review
+- `Images` and `Application CSV` zones with file counts.
+- `Matching review` section with:
+  - `Matched` group,
+  - `Ambiguous` group,
+  - `Unmatched images`,
+  - `Unmatched rows`.
+- Header showing counts for matched/ambiguous/unmatched.
+
+### CSV guidance (for this showcase)
+Required headers:
+- `filename`
+- `brand_name`
+- `class_type`
+- `alcohol_content`
+- `net_contents`
+
+Expected/full header set:
+- `fanciful_name`
+- `applicant_address`
+- `origin`
+- `country`
+- `formula_id`
+- `appellation`
+- `vintage`
+
+Speak this clearly during the run: 
+"I can add optional headers to preserve additional review context, but these five are what preflight requires to begin." 
+
+---
+
+## 05:00–06:00 — Batch dashboard, triage, and row drill-in
+
+### What you do
+1. On **Batch Results**, note summary cards (`Approve`, `Needs review`).
+2. Try filter pills:
+   - `All`
+   - `Needs review only`
+   - `Approves only`
+3. Try at least one sort option:
+   - `Worst first`, `Filename`, `Brand name`, `Order completed`.
+4. Open one row with label status `needs review`.
+5. In drill-down view:
+   - read verdict + evidence rows,
+   - use **Previous label** / **Next label**,
+   - use **Back to Batch Results**.
+6. Export results after validation.
+
+### What to say
+"This dashboard is where throughput stays manageable.
+
+You can filter by outcome, and the sorting lets you jump straight to the riskiest records.
+
+I’m opening one review row now. The drill-in view reuses the same evidence UI as single review, so reviewers do not relearn another interaction model.
+
+From here, you can export if you need a handoff artifact. Nothing is persisted server-side between sessions unless explicitly exported and downloaded.
+"
+
+### What you should see
+- Summary cards with final counts.
+- Filter pills and sort control.
+- Table row metadata:
+  - status icon,
+  - brand/class,
+  - issue summary (`must fix` / `important` / `minor`).
+- Export prompt with confirmation.
+- Drill-in has index line:
+  - `X of Y reviews` (or labels depending filter context).
+- `Back to Batch Results` navigation plus previous/next controls.
+
+---
+
+## Design highlights to narrate during recording
+
+Use one short line for each if you want to call out confidence/intentional design choices:
+
+- **Startup pause** was increased to avoid icon flicker; it is a usability and trust choice, not a delay for delay’s sake.
+- **Three-tier outcomes** in UI (approve / needs review / fail merged into review posture) keep the reviewer focused on actionable work.
+- **Field-level evidence** is mandatory for transparency; every row has explicit `Show evidence` action.
+- **Batch preflight** is done before processing so you control matching quality first.
+- **No-image/persistent-data posture** is clear in UI copy on intake and dashboard (`Nothing is stored`).
+- **Keyboard navigation** and clear controls are available for accessibility-first operation.
+
+---
+
+## Suggested narration cadence
+
+- Keep the voice slightly slower than usual: around **145–160 words per minute**.
+- Use longer pauses at these points:
+  - startup/auth (5 sec),
+  - single-result screen first pass (10 sec),
+  - warning evidence expansion (8–12 sec),
+  - batch preflight review (12–20 sec),
+  - batch dashboard filtering + drill-in (15–25 sec).
+
+That pacing normally yields a total run of ~4 minutes with good comprehension.
+
+---
+
+## Optional quality checkpoints (human validation)
+
+- Verify at least one batch row requires manual resolution in matching.
+- Verify one `Needs review` label in results.
+- Verify one `Approve` label in results.
+- Verify export flow can be confirmed/cancelled.
+- Verify batch drill-in row navigation updates index text correctly.
+- Verify `Show evidence` and `Hide evidence` transitions are visible.
+- Verify you can return to single mode from batch mode and continue.
+
+---
